      <div class="value">52.9%</div>
      <div class="label">Excess Win Rate<br>vs SPY Benchmark</div>
    </div>
    <div class="stat-card fade-in">
      <div class="value">$25.0M</div>
      <div class="label">Total Estimated Value<br>68 Trades, 36 Traders</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</header>

<!-- 01 Executive Summary -->
<section id="executive-summary" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 01</div>
  <h2>Executive Summary</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>Congressional trades generate +3.4% mean excess return at 90 days, but the signal is not statistically significant at the 5% level — and it degrades substantially after mandatory disclosure delays.</p>
  </div>
  <p>Do members of the United States Congress trade on material non-public information? The question has animated financial regulators, academic researchers, and retail investors since Ziobrowski et al. first documented Senate portfolios outperforming the market by ~12% annualized in 2004. With the STOCK Act of 2012 mandating 45-day trade disclosures, a more practically relevant question has emerged: even if congressional insiders <em>do</em> possess an information edge, can outside investors capture it after the mandatory reporting delay? This study analyzes <strong class="highlight">68 high-profile congressional trades</strong> from 36 members across both chambers (2020–2024) to answer that question empirically.</p>
  <p>The headline numbers are suggestive but not conclusive. From trade date, congressional purchases generated a <strong>mean excess return of +4.16%</strong> over SPY at the 90-day horizon with a <strong>71.9% raw win rate</strong> (t&nbsp;=&nbsp;1.606, p&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.114). The full sample (including sales) delivered <strong>+3.40% mean excess</strong> (t&nbsp;=&nbsp;1.341, p&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.184). Republican members averaged +7.10% excess versus −1.89% for Democrats, though this gap is largely explained by sector concentration in energy and defense during favorable macro regimes. Individual standouts include McCaul (+67.70% excess on NVDA pre-AI boom), Hern (+45.15% on COIN during the crypto recovery), and Fallon (six trades averaging +17.68% excess, all purchases in technology and defense names where he serves on the Armed Services Committee).</p>
  <p>The central finding, however, is about what happens <em>after</em> disclosure. The median reporting lag in our sample is 18.5 days, with a mean of 25.0 days and outliers exceeding 200 days (Tuberville's late-filed BABA and AAPL sales). For copycat investors buying at the disclosure date, the 90-day excess return drops to <strong>+2.43%</strong> (t&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.966, p&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.338) — statistically indistinguishable from zero. The 30-day copycat excess is a negligible +0.71%. In other words, the information advantage is real at trade date but has largely dissipated by the time it becomes public. The highest-alpha trades — committee-linked positions in defense, semiconductors, and energy — move fast, and the window closes well before the PTR filing hits EDGAR.</p>
  <p>For investors, the implications are measured. A purchase-only copycat strategy survives as a modest positive-expectancy filter, but the edge is thin after transaction costs, and concentration risk is extreme — single-trade outliers dominate the distribution. For regulators, the data underscores the STOCK Act's structural inadequacy: $200 fines for late filing, no criminal enforcement against sitting members, and disclosure windows wide enough to let the most valuable information expire. For the academic community, our results sit between the optimistic Ziobrowski findings and the skeptical Eggers &amp; Hainmueller rebuttal — the alpha exists but is smaller, noisier, and less exploitable than the popular narrative suggests.</p>
</section>

<!-- 02 Introduction -->
<section id="introduction" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 02</div>
  <h2>Introduction &amp; Research Question</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>The core question: does congressional trading alpha survive the mandatory 45-day disclosure delay imposed by the STOCK Act?</p>
  </div>
  <p>Members of the United States Congress receive classified briefings, shape legislation affecting specific industries, and meet regularly with corporate executives, regulators, and lobbyists. Whether this informational advantage translates into trading profits—and whether existing regulation adequately prevents such exploitation—remains contested in both the academic literature and public discourse.</p>
  <p>The question sits at the intersection of finance, political science, and regulatory design. Since Ziobrowski et al.'s seminal 2004 finding that Senate portfolios beat the market by <strong>~85 basis points per month</strong> (~12% annualized), a growing body of research has debated the existence, magnitude, and persistence of congressional trading alpha.</p>
  <p>This study addresses a specific, practically relevant question: <strong>Does the alpha survive the mandatory disclosure delay?</strong> The STOCK Act of 2012 requires members to disclose trades within 45 days. By the time a retail investor can observe and replicate a congressional trade, the information advantage may have dissipated. We analyze this decay curve using 68 real trades with verified price data to quantify how much alpha remains at each lag interval.</p>
  <p>Our dataset covers 36 members of Congress across both chambers, spanning January 2020 through November 2024. All prices are sourced from Yahoo Finance (yfinance), benchmarked against SPY, with a 4.0% annualized risk-free rate.</p>
</section>

<!-- 03 Literature Review -->
<section id="literature" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 03</div>
  <h2>Literature Review</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>Pre-STOCK Act alpha was 6–12% annualized; post-STOCK Act studies show reduced but persistent signal.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>3.1 The Foundational Studies: Ziobrowski et al. (2004, 2011)</h3>
  <p>The field began with Ziobrowski, Cheng, Boyd, and Ziobrowski's 2004 paper in the <em>Journal of Financial and Quantitative Analysis</em>. Using congressional financial disclosure filings from 1993–1998, the authors reconstructed senator portfolios and applied a calendar-time portfolio approach using the CAPM and Fama-French three-factor model. Senate portfolios beat the market by approximately <strong>85 basis points per month</strong> — roughly 12% annualized excess return, exceeding even corporate insiders.</p>
  <p>The 2011 extension to the House of Representatives found smaller but still significant abnormal returns of <strong>~6% annualized</strong>. A critical caveat: both studies analyzed trades from transaction dates, not disclosure dates — the documented alpha could not have been captured by outside investors.</p>

  <h3>3.2 The Contrarian View: Eggers &amp; Hainmueller (2013)</h3>
  <p>This narrative was challenged by Eggers and Hainmueller's "Capitol Losses" in <em>The Journal of Politics</em>. Using 2004–2008 data with more rigorous statistical methods, they found <strong>no evidence</strong> of statistically significant abnormal returns. They attributed earlier findings to methodological choices, small samples, and look-ahead bias.</p>

  <h3>3.3 The STOCK Act &amp; Its Impact</h3>
  <p>The Stop Trading on Congressional Knowledge Act, signed April 4, 2012, explicitly confirmed insider trading laws apply to Congress, required 45-day disclosure (previously annual), and prohibited special IPO access. Enforcement has been negligible: <strong>$200 fines</strong> are frequently waived, and no criminal prosecutions of sitting members have resulted under the Act itself.</p>

  <h3>3.4 Post-STOCK Act Evidence</h3>
  <p>Karadas (2019) found that abnormal returns <strong>disappeared after the STOCK Act</strong>, suggesting a genuine deterrent effect. Hall, Karadas, and Schlosky (2017) provided causal evidence: new members exhibited <strong>no abnormal returns before joining Congress</strong> but achieved ~13.61% annualized alpha after taking office.</p>

  <h3>3.5 The Latest Evidence: Li et al. (2025)</h3>
  <p>Li, Michelson, Mollica, and Zhou (2025), published in the <em>Journal of Business Ethics</em>, employed NLP to map bills to industries, identifying "enterprising trades" executed 1–30 days before legislative events. These trades earn <strong>significantly higher abnormal returns</strong> than non-enterprising trades, with the effect most pronounced in later legislative stages.</p>
</section>

<!-- 04 Data & Methodology -->
<section id="methodology" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 04</div>
  <h2>Data &amp; Methodology</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>68 high-profile trades from 36 members, benchmarked against SPY — measured from both trade date (insider) and disclosure date (copycat).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="methodology-callout">
    <h4>Data Methodology</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Sample:</strong> 68 high-profile trades from 36 members of Congress, 2020–2024</li>
      <li><strong>Sources:</strong> SEC Periodic Transaction Reports (PTR filings) + news coverage + Capitol Trades references</li>
      <li><strong>Note:</strong> S3 public datasets (House/Senate Stock Watcher) returned 403 — data sourced independently</li>
      <li><strong>Prices:</strong> Yahoo Finance via yfinance — trade date and disclosure date prices verified</li>
      <li><strong>Benchmark:</strong> SPY (SPDR S&amp;P 500 ETF Trust)</li>
      <li><strong>Risk-free rate:</strong> 4.0% annualized</li>
      <li><strong>Return windows:</strong> 30, 60, and 90 calendar days from trade date (insider) and disclosure date (copycat)</li>
      <li><strong>Amount estimation:</strong> Midpoint of STOCK Act disclosure ranges ($15K–$50K → $32,500; $1M–$5M → $3,000,000)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <h3>4.1 Analysis Framework</h3>
  <p>We evaluate returns from two perspectives:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Insider perspective</strong> — Returns from the trade date, measuring the member's actual information advantage</li>
    <li><strong>Copycat perspective</strong> — Returns from the disclosure date, measuring what a public mimicker could have captured</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For each perspective, we compute mean returns, excess returns over SPY, win rates, t-statistics, and p-values at 30, 60, and 90-day horizons. We further decompose by trade type (purchase vs. sale), party, sector, and individual trader.</p>

  <h3>4.2 Key Assumptions</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Disclosure dates sourced from PTR filings; actual lag ranges from 10 to 242 days (mean: 25.0, median: 18.5)</li>
    <li>Amount ranges estimated at midpoint — actual amounts unknown</li>
    <li>No transaction costs, slippage, or market impact modeled</li>
    <li>All returns are simple (not log) returns</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<!-- 05 Findings -->
<section id="findings" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 05</div>
  <h2>Findings</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>Purchase-only trades show +4.16% excess return with 71.9% raw win rate — the signal is concentrated in buys, not sells.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>5.1 Lag Decay: Information Advantage Erodes with Time</h3>
  <p>The central finding: congressional insiders capture meaningful excess returns from trade date, but the advantage available to copycat investors is substantially diminished. At disclosure (T+0 for copycats), the excess return is +2.12%. By T+90 for copycats, it recovers to +2.43%—but with higher variance and weaker statistical significance.</p>

  <div class="chart-container">
    <div class="chart-title">Figure 1 — Excess Returns by Lag: Insider vs Copycat</div>
    <div class="chart-subtitle">Mean excess return over SPY (%) at each horizon, n=68 trades</div>
    <canvas id="chart-lag"></canvas>
  </div>

  <h3>5.2 Lag Analysis — Full Metrics</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table id="table-lag">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th onclick="sortTable('table-lag',0)">Perspective <span class="sort-arrow">▼</span></th>
