          <th onclick="sortTable('table-lag',4)">Win Rate <span class="sort-arrow">▼</span></th>
          <th onclick="sortTable('table-lag',5)">Excess Win <span class="sort-arrow">▼</span></th>
          <th onclick="sortTable('table-lag',6)">t-Stat <span class="sort-arrow">▼</span></th>
          <th onclick="sortTable('table-lag',7)">p-Value <span class="sort-arrow">▼</span></th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Insider</td><td>At Disclosure</td><td class="num">3.69%</td><td class="num positive">+2.12%</td><td class="num">66.2%</td><td class="num">54.4%</td><td class="num">1.164</td><td class="num">0.248</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Insider</td><td>T+30d</td><td class="num">4.42%</td><td class="num positive">+2.17%</td><td class="num">63.2%</td><td class="num">51.5%</td><td class="num">1.066</td><td class="num">0.290</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Insider</td><td>T+60d</td><td class="num">6.11%</td><td class="num positive">+2.58%</td><td class="num">66.2%</td><td class="num">52.9%</td><td class="num">1.153</td><td class="num">0.253</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Insider</td><td>T+90d</td><td class="num">7.92%</td><td class="num positive">+3.40%</td><td class="num">66.2%</td><td class="num">52.9%</td><td class="num">1.341</td><td class="num">0.184</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Copycat</td><td>T+30d</td><td class="num">1.58%</td><td class="num positive">+0.71%</td><td class="num">51.5%</td><td class="num">41.2%</td><td class="num">0.456</td><td class="num">0.650</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Copycat</td><td>T+60d</td><td class="num">3.68%</td><td class="num positive">+1.52%</td><td class="num">61.8%</td><td class="num">47.1%</td><td class="num">0.670</td><td class="num">0.505</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Copycat</td><td>T+90d</td><td class="num">5.61%</td><td class="num positive">+2.43%</td><td class="num">55.9%</td><td class="num">52.9%</td><td class="num">0.966</td><td class="num">0.338</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Purchases Only</td><td>T+30d</td><td class="num">6.61%</td><td class="num positive">+3.24%</td><td class="num">54.4%</td><td class="num">54.4%</td><td class="num">1.542</td><td class="num">0.129</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Purchases Only</td><td>T+60d</td><td class="num">8.52%</td><td class="num positive">+3.52%</td><td class="num">56.1%</td><td class="num">56.1%</td><td class="num">1.596</td><td class="num">0.116</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Purchases Only</td><td>T+90d</td><td class="num">10.27%</td><td class="num positive">+4.16%</td><td class="num">56.1%</td><td class="num">56.1%</td><td class="num">1.606</td><td class="num">0.114</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Sales Only</td><td>T+30d</td><td class="num negative">−6.92%</td><td class="num negative">−3.37%</td><td class="num">36.4%</td><td class="num">36.4%</td><td class="num">−0.533</td><td class="num">0.606</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Sales Only</td><td>T+60d</td><td class="num negative">−6.39%</td><td class="num negative">−2.28%</td><td class="num">36.4%</td><td class="num">36.4%</td><td class="num">−0.286</td><td class="num">0.781</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Sales Only</td><td>T+90d</td><td class="num negative">−4.30%</td><td class="num negative">−0.52%</td><td class="num">36.4%</td><td class="num">36.4%</td><td class="num">−0.062</td><td class="num">0.952</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3>5.3 Cumulative Monthly Returns</h3>
  <p>Monthly mean excess returns exhibit considerable volatility, with clusters of outperformance during market dislocations (COVID bottom in Q1 2020, regional banking crisis in Q1 2023, AI boom in H2 2023) and underperformance during range-bound periods.</p>

  <div class="chart-container">
    <div class="chart-title">Figure 2 — Monthly Mean Excess Returns (90-Day Horizon)</div>
    <div class="chart-subtitle">Congressional trades vs SPY by month, insider perspective</div>
    <canvas id="chart-cumulative"></canvas>
  </div>

  <h3>5.4 Party Comparison</h3>
  <p>Republican members significantly outperformed Democrats in this sample. The 40 Republican trades averaged <strong class="highlight">+7.10% excess return</strong> at 90 days, versus <strong>−1.89%</strong> for the 28 Democratic trades (t=−1.772, p=0.081). This difference approaches significance at the 10% level.</p>

  <div class="chart-container">
    <div class="chart-title">Figure 3 — Party Comparison: Mean Excess Return at 90 Days</div>
    <div class="chart-subtitle">Republican (n=40) vs Democrat (n=28) trades</div>
    <canvas id="chart-party"></canvas>
  </div>

  <h3>5.5 Sector Analysis</h3>
  <p>Consumer Discretionary leads with a <strong>+10.21% mean excess return</strong> (driven largely by Tesla trades), followed by Financials at +8.84%. Technology, despite being the most-traded sector (32 trades), shows a more modest +2.65% excess return—the larger sample dilutes outlier performance.</p>

  <div class="chart-container">
    <div class="chart-title">Figure 4 — Sector Excess Returns (90-Day)</div>
    <div class="chart-subtitle">Mean excess return (%) by sector, with trade counts</div>
    <canvas id="chart-sectors"></canvas>
  </div>

  <h3>5.6 Top Traders by Excess Return</h3>
  <p>The highest-alpha traders tend to have <strong>very few trades</strong>—single-trade performers like McCaul (+67.70% on NVDA) and Hern (+45.15% on COIN) dominate. Among multi-trade members, Pat Fallon (6 trades, +17.68% mean excess) and Josh Gottheimer (2 trades, +18.74%) stand out. Pelosi, the most visible trader (13 trades, $14.8M estimated volume), shows a <strong>−2.71% mean excess return</strong>—her TSLA and CRM wins are offset by losses on RBLX, PANW, and DIS.</p>

