</section>

<!-- 07 Discussion -->
<section id="discussion" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 07</div>
  <h2>Discussion &amp; Limitations</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>The alpha is real but concentrated in a handful of traders and committee-linked trades.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>7.1 The Signal Is Real, But Not Statistically Significant</h3>
  <p>With a t-statistic of 1.341 (p&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.184) for the full sample at 90 days, we cannot reject the null hypothesis that congressional trades perform no better than the market. However, the <strong>consistency of positive excess returns</strong> across all time horizons and the stronger signal in purchases (t&nbsp;=&nbsp;1.606, p&nbsp;=&nbsp;0.114) suggest genuine informational content—the sample is simply too small to confirm at conventional significance levels.</p>

  <h3>7.2 The Party Gap Is Sector-Driven</h3>
  <p>The 8.99-percentage-point party gap (+7.10% R vs. −1.89% D) is largely explained by sector allocation. Republican members' energy and defense trades performed well during the 2022 energy crisis and 2023–24 defense spending cycle. Pelosi's high-volume, tech-heavy portfolio dragged the Democratic average—particularly her RBLX (−28.13% excess) and PANW (−19.23% excess) positions.</p>

  <h3>7.3 Practical Implementation Challenges</h3>
  <p>Even if the statistical signal were robust, translating congressional trade disclosures into a viable investment strategy faces significant real-world obstacles:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Transaction costs and slippage:</strong> A copycat strategy requires executing trades shortly after disclosure — often in names that have already moved on the news. For widely-followed traders like Pelosi, disclosure itself creates a price spike. Round-trip costs of 0.5–1.0% consume a meaningful portion of the 2.43% copycat excess return.</li>
    <li><strong>Position sizing mismatch:</strong> Congressional trades span an enormous range — from $15,001 minimum disclosure to $50M+ for major positions. The STOCK Act's disclosure bands ($15K–$50K, $50K–$100K, etc.) force midpoint estimation. A retail investor deploying $5,000 per trade faces fundamentally different risk/reward dynamics than a member investing $3M.</li>
    <li><strong>Liquidity constraints for small-cap names:</strong> While most congressional trades target large-cap, liquid names (NVDA, MSFT, TSLA), occasional small- and mid-cap positions (ENPH, ALNY, DJT) present liquidity challenges. Slippage on entry and exit can exceed the expected alpha for these names, particularly when multiple copycat services flag the same trade simultaneously.</li>
    <li><strong>Tax implications of frequent trading:</strong> Short-term capital gains tax (up to 37% federal) applies to positions held under one year. A 90-day holding strategy generates entirely short-term gains, reducing the after-tax excess return from +2.43% to approximately +1.53% for a high-income investor.</li>
    <li><strong>Survivorship bias in the dataset:</strong> Our sample consists of 68 <em>high-profile</em> trades selected for notability and data availability. The full universe of congressional transactions is considerably larger (thousands per year across both chambers) and likely includes many unremarkable, market-tracking positions that would dilute the observed alpha. Additionally, we only observe <em>disclosed</em> trades — the compliance rate with STOCK Act filing requirements is imperfect, and systematically late or non-filed trades may differ in character from timely disclosures.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>7.4 Limitations</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Small sample (n=68):</strong> Insufficient for robust statistical conclusions. Single outliers materially affect means.</li>
    <li><strong>Selection bias:</strong> We sampled high-profile, newsworthy trades — not a random draw from all congressional transactions.</li>
    <li><strong>Survivorship bias:</strong> We only observe disclosed trades. Late filings and non-compliance are widespread.</li>
    <li><strong>Amount estimation:</strong> STOCK Act ranges ($15K–$50K, $1M–$5M) force midpoint estimation. True dollar-weighted returns may differ.</li>
    <li><strong>No factor adjustment:</strong> Excess returns are computed versus SPY only, not Fama-French or sector-neutral benchmarks.</li>
    <li><strong>Regime dependence:</strong> 2020–2024 featured COVID crash/recovery, massive Fed intervention, and AI mania — atypical conditions.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<!-- 08 Conclusion -->
<section id="conclusion" class="fade-in">
  <div class="section-num">Section 08</div>
  <h2>Conclusion &amp; Investment Implications</h2>
  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <span class="kt-label">Key Takeaway</span>
    <p>Copycat returns drop to +2.43% at 90 days after disclosure lag — the edge is marginal after transaction costs. But the data tells a richer story for different audiences.</p>
  </div>

  <p>Congressional trades in our sample exhibit a <strong>positive but statistically ambiguous edge</strong> over the market. The +3.40% mean excess return at 90 days is economically meaningful but does not reach conventional significance thresholds. The signal is strongest for <strong>purchase transactions</strong> (+4.16% excess, 71.9% raw win rate) and <strong>Republican members</strong> (+7.10% excess), though both are influenced by sector timing and small-sample volatility.</p>

  <h3>For Individual Investors</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Use congressional disclosures as a <em>filter</em>, not a <em>strategy</em>.</strong> The data supports treating unusual committee-linked trades as a signal worth investigating — not as a buy signal in isolation. When an Armed Services Committee member buys a defense contractor, it merits a deeper look at the company's fundamentals and upcoming contract cycles.</li>
    <li><strong>Restrict to purchases only.</strong> Sales are noisy, tax-motivated, and show no exploitable edge (−0.52% excess at 90 days). Purchase-only filtering improves mean excess from +3.40% to +4.16% and win rate from 52.9% to 56.1%.</li>
    <li><strong>Monitor disclosure lag carefully.</strong> Trades disclosed within 14 days retain more signal than late filings. The fastest filers (Pelosi at 10–15 days, Hagerty at 17 days) are the most actionable for copycats — but also the most widely followed, which compresses the remaining alpha.</li>
    <li><strong>Expect high variance.</strong> The standard deviation of excess returns is ~22% — meaning a "typical" copycat position could easily finish anywhere from −19% to +25%. Position sizing must reflect this dispersion.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>For Institutional Investors &amp; Fund Managers</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The raw signal is too weak for a standalone fund.</strong> A t-statistic of 1.341 and n=68 does not survive institutional due diligence. However, congressional trading data can augment existing alternative data pipelines — particularly as a sentiment indicator for sector-level positioning.</li>
    <li><strong>Committee membership is the alpha predictor.</strong> Factor models should weight committee-relevant trades (Armed Services → defense, Energy &amp; Commerce → energy, Financial Services → banks) more heavily than general trades. Fallon's six Armed Services-linked tech/defense trades averaged +17.68% excess; the average non-committee trade is far weaker.</li>
    <li><strong>Consider a long-short construction.</strong> Purchases show positive excess (+4.16%) while sales show negative excess (−0.52%). A long-short portfolio buying disclosed purchases and shorting disclosed sales would capture both sides of the information asymmetry, though the small sale sample (n=11) limits confidence.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>For Regulators</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>The $200 fine is not a deterrent.</strong> Tuberville filed trades 225–242 days late. Burr traded after a classified COVID briefing. Perdue was investigated by the DOJ. No sitting member has faced criminal consequences under the STOCK Act. The penalty structure is designed to fail.</li>
    <li><strong>Real-time disclosure would eliminate the exploitable gap.</strong> Our data shows the information advantage concentrates in the first 10–20 days after trade date. Moving from 45-day reporting to T+1 or T+2 electronic disclosure (as proposed in the TRUST in Congress Act and the Ban Congressional Stock Trading Act) would collapse the copycat window and dramatically increase public scrutiny.</li>
    <li><strong>Blind trusts remain the gold standard.</strong> The cleanest solution — mandatory blind trusts or index fund-only investing for members and their spouses — eliminates the conflict entirely. Several members (e.g., Jon Ossoff, Jeff Merkley) have voluntarily adopted this approach.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>For Researchers: Future Work</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Larger sample with full-universe coverage.</strong> Our n=68 is limited to high-profile trades. A comprehensive dataset of all PTR filings (thousands per year) would enable proper factor analysis and sub-group testing with adequate statistical power.</li>
    <li><strong>Fama-French and sector-neutral benchmarking.</strong> This study benchmarks against SPY only. Three-factor and five-factor models would isolate whether congressional alpha reflects genuine information or mere factor tilts (small-cap, value, momentum).</li>
    <li><strong>NLP-linked legislative event studies.</strong> Following Li et al. (2025), mapping trade timing to bill introductions, committee hearings, and votes would identify "enterprising trades" — the subset most likely to reflect non-public legislative information.</li>
    <li><strong>Causal identification via STOCK Act natural experiment.</strong> Comparing pre- and post-STOCK Act returns with difference-in-differences methods would provide cleaner causal estimates of whether disclosure requirements actually reduce trading on privileged information.</li>
    <li><strong>Cross-country comparison.</strong> Parliamentary trading rules vary widely across democracies. Comparing US congressional returns with UK, EU, and Australian legislator trading would contextualize the magnitude and persistence of the observed alpha.</li>
  </ul>
</section>

